# Circle vs Ellipse

::: {.callout-warning}

Circles are a special type of ellipse where the **semi-major axis** and **semi-minor axis** are equal.  
This means the two foci merge at the centre, and every point on the curve is the same distance from the centre.  

Use the sliders below to explore both shapes and see how changing the axes affects their appearance.

:::

::: {.callout-tip}

Try changing the **ellipse axes** and the **circle radius**:  

- Notice how the ellipse stretches horizontally or vertically depending on \(a\) and \(b\).  
- Observe how the circle stays perfectly round regardless of the radius.  
- When \(a = b\) for the ellipse, it **becomes a circle**, showing that a circle is a “perfect ellipse.”

:::

